"{\"uid\": \"forbes.com-sites-sophiekaufman-2024-08-01-why-katie-ledecky-will-likely-head-to-her-fifth-olympics-in-la\", \"text\": \"BySophie Kaufman,  Contributor.  On one of the best nights of racing in the pool at the 2024 Olympic Games, Katie Ledecky contributed to the show by extending her reign over women's distance freestyle. Ledecky dominated the field in the women's 1500-meter freestyle, defending her Olympic title from the inaugural edition of the race in Tokyo. Ledecky won the race by 10.33 seconds, claiming ownership of all top 20 performances in the event.  Already a legend in the sport, this gold medal further cements Ledecky's status as one of the greatest swimmers in history. It's her eighth Olympic gold, tying her for the most by an American woman in any sport. It's also her twelfth Olympic medal overall, moving her into a tie with Jenny Thompson, Dara Torres, Natalie Coughlin, and Emma McKeon for most Olympic medals won by a female swimmer.  Ledecky still has more events to come at these Games, including the 800-meter freestyle, where she is aiming for more history with a fourth consecutive win. And it does not sound like she is done making history beyond these Games.  \\\"I have been consistent over these last few months and last few years in saying that I would love to compete in L.A. and that has not changed,\\\" LedeckytoldESPNafter the 1500-meter freestyle. \\\"That could change. I mean, you never know. So, I really just take it year by year at this point and I really have not thought much beyond this week in terms of what my fall is going to look like, what my next year is going to look like. But yeah, I do not feel like I am close to being finished in the sport yet.\\\"  Ledecky broke out on the international scene at the 2012 Olympic Games. At 15, she was the youngest member of Team USA at those Games but stunned the women's 800-meter freestyle field, winning gold by more than four seconds.  She would be 31 during the 2028 Los Angeles Games. She's already one of the veterans on the U.S. Olympic swimming roster at 27 years old and on her fourth Olympic team. As a sport, swimming is becoming younger; teenagers like Canadian sensation Summer McIntosh-who beat Ledecky for silver earlier this week in the 400-meter freestyle-are quickly working their way to the top.  As Ledecky continues racing, her consistency is one of the most impressive parts of her incredible career. It's that continued excellence and her longevity that, should Ledecky compete in LA, would cement her as the greatest swimmer of all time. No swimmer has won an event at five Olympics. Only four women have won Olympic gold after their 30th birthday.  While swimmers often swim into their thirties, the veterans usually shine in the sprint events and relays. It's rare to see the older distance swimmers on the top step of the Olympic podium. But if she wants to be there in four years, Ledecky has all the tools she needs to be there. In the 12 years since the London Games, Ledecky has redefined women's swimming and distance freestyle. She shows no signs of slowing down as she continues to chart a historic career trajectory. In May, LedeckytoldNBC,\\\"The [2028] Olympics being in LA is very appealing. Not very many athletes get an opportunity to compete in a home Games.\\\"  We are currently seeing the effect an athlete dominating their home Games can have with Leon Marchandin Paris. Ledecky stepping up to the blocks for an Olympic final in the United States, ready to make more history, would undoubtedly be a special moment in a career defined by consistent domination.\"}"